body.plain: This song is about how the speaker got into a relationship, was happy in the relationship, and then he left her. She however is still waiting for him to come to his senses, but she feels like a fool for doing it.

annotations:
I love to see you
 Way over there
Her crush feels distant; she feels like they don’t quite fit together, and so she watches and keeps her distance rather than forcing herself into this person’s life.

Your name is a triangle
 Your heart is a square
She can’t figure him out, or how to fit in with him. Like a square peg in a round hole, it’s just not going to work.

I thought we could eat bread
 I thought we could talk
 On darker days
 With our boots kicked off
 You look to me
 And I look away
 Though I had been looking

Like most people, Greta fantasized about a future with her crush, romanticizing what life would have been like and thinking about particular scenarios. But these dreams only furthered the pain that she felt once reality struck her.

You make me feel like a fool waiting for you
 You make me feel like a fool waiting for you

After being stood up, Greta feels an immense sense of embarrassment after letting her guard down. As soon as she felt that something good had happened in her life, that feeling was swiftly taken away from her.

Once I was happy
 You found it intriguing
 Then you got to me
 And left me waiting
On a particularly good day for Greta, her crush/interest notices her and asks her on a date (hence “[getting] to [her]”), though when the time came her date did not show.

Throughout the song, Kline becomes closer to the subject of the song, and her feelings and anxiety only grow as she does so.

annotations: Is it cool when I don’t care?
Indifference is often seen as an attractive trait to have
Is it cool when I don’t care?
Indifference is often seen as an attractive trait to have

So I look up into your window
 From the street where I am standing (So I look up into your window)
 Is that even your house? (From the street where I’m standing)
 Is that your landing? (Is that even your house?)
 And I wanna know what (Is that your landing?)
 You’re readin

The narrator is stalking this person, or at least attempting to, but does not even know if they have their address correct or recognize the face of the person reading. They know very little about the person they are enamored with.

I am too stressed out to
 Do the thing that they won’t do
haha, get it? the thing the train won’t do is “come”

Your face too close to mine
 To hear you talk

This echoes a line from Sappho fragment 31, her most famous (and most frequently translated) poem:

“He seems to me equal to the gods that man
whoever he is who opposite you
sits and listens close
to your sweet speaking
and lovely laughing”
(translated by Anne Carson)

You can read a wide range of translations of the poem here http://www.bopsecrets.org/gateway/passages/sappho.htm.
Is that Sappho you’re readin’?

Sappho was an lesbian poet in ancient Greece, widely regarded as one of the greatest poets of all time. Plato called her the Tenth Muse. She was noted for writing (and singing)  confessional lyric poetry in the first person – not unlike Frankie Cosmos' lyrics. Although she wrote nine volumes of poetry, we’ve lost most of her work. Today, we only have one complete poem by her and a bunch of fragments.

There are a couple subtle Sappho references sprinkled throughout the rest of the song, particularly to her famous Fragment 31. Also, Frankie Cosmos' short song lengths echo Sappho’s fragments.

Kline feels as though she is unfinished/rough without this person. she is only good and polished when they are together.
I’m a cast iron

Cast-iron cookware is rarely cleaned, and instead collects residues of everything cooked in it (spices, oils etc.), giving each piece a unique character over time. Here Greta expands on the previous cooking imagery and identifies with this process: she’s able to reckon with her past just by seeing where she is now.

description.plain:
“Outside With the Cuties” is about friendship in love, with an emphasis on being a third wheel looking for a fourth. Kline watches her friends (who are dating) from a distance and feels like she is missing out or feeling unwelcome.

To combat this, she finds someone herself and struggles to make a connection until the end of the song, where she comes to a sense of completion with her partner.

The line “I haven’t written this part yet” and “I haven’t finished this song yet” track her progress within the song, serving as marks of transition.

annotations:
I haven’t finished this song yet
 Will you help me fix it
This is parallel to asking for help, but rather than asking for guidance, Kline seeks a more critical and involved editor in her partner. In this way, her love would be more present.

I haven’t written this part yet
 Will you help me write it?
Writing is a way for Kline to cope, but she wants the company of writing with a partner instead of writing alone.
I guess it’s not really brave

Often times, people who live far from home can be seen as acting brave in doing so, since family is an emotional tether that helps people remain calm. Since Greta is away from home, she feels the weight of having no close friends or family around, and copes by writing this song, which she sees as succumbing to weakness.

Can’t see you cry, you’re down the street
 I wonder when you’ll talk to me

Despite her friend’s annoying pessimism, she wants them to open up to her. Her friend seems to be closed off from her. In an interview with Fuze.tv, she had this to say:

“‘I think touring makes you a worse friend,’ … ‘I just feel like I’m making things worse. Every time I come home, I’m like, ‘Eh, I have less friends now.’”

You are bug bites on vacation
 You find the sad in everything

Greta notes some of the less desirable characteristics of the person that she’s with, be it a friend or more. “They are bug bites on vacation” means they can be annoying during times that are supposed to be happy and enjoyable, and “you find the sad in everything” is self explanatory—they tend to be a pessimist.

annotations:
I just wanna be alive, that’s it
 
 Alive
 Alive

A very simple statement that provokes deep thought and very intense emotion. Kline has to deal with her anxiety, her self-image, her status and her art while also being pressured to have ‘fun’ and be ‘young’, like others around her. It’s hard and overwhelming, but she feels that pressure because she also wants it for herself. She wants to live happily, to have experiences and make memories and be alive. She wants to be young.

“Easy for you to say,” I say
 I say this to you every day
 Easy for you to say

Kline points out that ‘having fun/being young and wild’ is easier said than done, and to her it is much more difficult to achieve. The person she is speaking to makes it seem easy, because they are perfectly capable of going out and having fun without a thought.

The sky is a special orange streak
 Between balloons, two moons
 A leak of light in a blue town like this
 The clouds are you, the sky a kiss
 That never shows or comes oh what
 A waste sits in the parking lot

Here, it sounds like she is describing a date that stood her up. “The clouds are you, the sky is a kiss that never shows or comes” could hint that she was expecting a kiss, but it never happened because her date never showed up. As she describes the sun setting and the day ending with vivid and poetic imagery as she sits in the parking lot observing, she could be thinking about what a waste it was to spend the day alone, waiting.

I heard about being young
 But I’m not sure how it’s done
 Thought I heard a mumble
 Something about “fun”
 Fun
 Fun

This is a very hyperbolic statement, which emphasizes on the idea that she has never really felt like she goes out much or has too many real ‘fun’ experiences, like a normal, reckless young teenager.
In an interview, Greta Kline said that the song ‘Art School’ was about a time when Kline was about 18 years old and her boyfriend Aaron Maine was about 24. She mentioned that all of her friends had just started college and were lonely and sad, whereas Maine’s friends were having a lot of fun. ‘Anxiety and stress about school versus having fun and being wild could’ be a continued motif throughout her songs.

With this I’m scrapin’ by
 At least it’s cute that I tried
 I wrote some songs that I sung

This quote illustrates the very unfulfilling life of an underground artist – she is barely scraping by, making enough money and generating just enough of a fanbase to get by alone. She feels inadequate and insecure about her music, her achievements and the life that she leads.

And have you heard I am so young?
 And who my parents are?

Regarding these lines, Greta had this to say to Pitchfork:

“[Age is] a rife topic. Two of the most literal lines in “Young” are: “Have you heard I am so young/ And who my parents are?” They’re the two things that somehow legitimized me, or gave people some reason to talk about me, whether or not they liked my music. Maybe it was a little bit about that fear—Am I a real artist, or is this the reason people are interested? It was stressful.”
